04878nam a22006135i 9780822392293DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223922937 a10.1515/97808223922932doi  a(DE-B1597)554439  a(OCoLC)320539097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aQE697b.O79 2005 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a560/.17922221 aKawashima, Ken C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Proletarian Gamble :bKorean Workers in Interwar Japan /cKen C. Kawashima; Masao Miyoshi, Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (308 p.) :b31 tables, 1 map, 6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Proletarian Gamble -- t1. The Birth of the Uncontrollable Colonial Surplus -- t2. The Colonial Surplus and the Virtual Pauper -- t3. Intermediary Exploitation -- t4. Urban Expropriation and the Threat of the Outside -- t5. The Obscene, Violent Supplement of State Power -- t6. At the Gates of Unemployment -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix 1 Korean Self-help and Social Work Organizations in Japan -- tAppendix 2 A Timeline of Anti-Sōaikai Activity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKoreans constituted the largest colonial labor force in imperial Japan during the 1920s and 1930s. Caught between the Scylla of agricultural destitution in Korea and the Charybdis of industrial depression in Japan, migrant Korean peasants arrived on Japanese soil amid extreme instability in the labor and housing markets. In The Proletarian Gamble, Ken C. Kawashima maintains that contingent labor is a defining characteristic of capitalist commodity economies. He scrutinizes how the labor power of Korean workers in Japan was commodified, and how these workers both fought against the racist and contingent conditions of exchange and combated institutionalized racism.Kawashima draws on previously unseen archival materials from interwar Japan as he describes how Korean migrants struggled against various recruitment practices, unfair and discriminatory wages, sudden firings, racist housing practices, and excessive bureaucratic red tape. Demonstrating that there was no single Korean "minority," he reveals how Koreans exploited fellow Koreans and how the stratification of their communities worked to the advantage of state and capital. However, Kawashima also describes how, when migrant workers did organize-as when they became involved in Rōsō (the largest Korean communist labor union in Japan) and in Zenkyō (the Japanese communist labor union)-their diverse struggles were united toward a common goal. In The Proletarian Gamble, his analysis of the Korean migrant workers' experiences opens into a much broader rethinking of the fundamental nature of capitalist commodity economies and the analytical categories of the proletariat, surplus populations, commodification, and state power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aGlacial epochvJuvenile literature. 0aGlaciersvJuvenile literature. 0aKoreansxEmploymentzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor supplyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392293zCo-access DOI >> click Wal